    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's definitely challenging when there isn't clear evidence of theft or unrecorded transactions. Considering the explanations so far don't add up, I'd look into more obscure possibilities. One could be RFID mismatches or software bugs specific to certain SKUs that don't trigger alerts or alarms. Another consideration might be a systematic issue, such as an inventory software that fails to update properly when certain conditions are met or an accidental but overlooked integration with another system that's not performing as expected. It's also useful to review recent changes to warehouse processes, third-party integrations, or software updates that correlate with the starting of the discrepancies.\n\nConsider also the potential for human error through 'phantom' inventory adjustments or misinterpreted visual cues, or even animals, depending on the density of the warehouse. Ultimately, a cross-functional team with IT, warehouse management, and security professionals reviewing logs, software, and recent changes in warehouse operations could uncover a scenario that escaped earlier attention, or perhaps it's an administrative oversight like failing to fully reconcile the WMS with the actual stock.",
